WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Okay, now we mark the first three takes. Good, thank you. Now we're going straight through.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Today is Monday, March 18, 2013. My name is John Dittmer and I'm here in Baltimore, Maryland with videographer John Bishop.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
To interview Martha Prescod Norman Noonan, an activist in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:40.000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, DC.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
We're delighted to be here and thanks for taking time to talk with us.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Now let's start with your family background. Where were you born and raised? Tell us something about your folks, your early experiences.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:03.000
I was born and raised in Providence, Rhode Island. My father was a West Indian descent. He was from the island of St. Vincent.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And he had migrated to Brooklyn in the early 1920s.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:25.000
We're about a decade later he met my mother who was born in Ann Arbor, Michigan and went to New York to work in one of the New Deal alphabet agencies.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:37.000
And when she showed up of course there was no job. And so they, anyway, they met during the Depression and they married and he became an optometrist.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And they moved to Rhode Island. They were both activists. My father, I remember early my father was involved in some efforts for Pan-West-Indian unity.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:14.000
My mother came from a family that had migrated to Buxton, Ontario in the 1850s and her grandfather was an activist.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And why can't I think of his name at this moment?

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:30.000
But he was active in the Colored Conventions Movement. He was a minister. And so they had that tradition in her family.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:40.000
In Rhode Island they joined the Progressive Party. One point my father was a State Chairman of the Progressive Party.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.000
That was a left-wing organization.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
I guess so.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And then he got into trouble.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Well, yes he did actually. What I started to say was they tell me that my first political act was they took me to a, when I was three, they took me to an event for Henry A. Wallace.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I was running for president. And I must have heard conversation, proceeding to thing. And when his talk was over, I went up to him in that voice, one of those loud voices that only a three-year-old can do.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.000
And said, well, you look like a nice man.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:38.000
And he was so taken with it that he, I posed with him. And our picture was on the front page of the Providence Journal. They tell me I always wanted to go back and look that up.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:56.000
But, yeah, after his involvement, and I remember this event quite clearly, I think it was somebody from the FBI or for the immigration authority came to our house and threatened to deport him even though he was a naturalized citizen.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And I also remember that one of the other gentlemen in the group who owned a factory, a jewelry factory that was big in Providence, watches, costumes jewelry, where my father had worked as he was losing his sight.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:25.000
He was called before HUAC. And he knew that his financial life would be over just because of being called. And of course that was also on the front page of the Providence Journal.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And he was a immigrant here, house in America. He committed suicide. He was very sad.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:41.000
So my parents were very careful about activism.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:56.000
They did other things like try to get a black teacher in the public schools. I think they were successful with that. And different ad hoc things as they came along.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
What was it like growing up in Providence, Rhode Island, majority of White County in the North?

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Well, it wasn't very pleasant for me. And some of that was my parents' decision.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:21.000
My father began losing his sight when I was around five. He self-diagnosed. He knew he had glaucoma.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:33.000
And so part of what they did, anticipating that his salary, the finances in the household would be less. They closed his office.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:41.000
And bought a house that was an old funeral parlor and a white neighbor. Now we lived in a white neighborhood previously.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:51.000
But this particular neighborhood was not happy about our coming there. People threw stones to the window.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:08.000
A few times I got beaten up, going back and forth to school. I got called all kinds of names. One of the first time I ever heard, I'm black and I'm proud, was from my mother, who told me as a young child.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:19.000
It must have been about six years old. She said when people call you a dirty black nigger, she said, you don't respond with any ethnic neighborhood, too.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:28.000
She said, don't respond with any ethnic slurs. You say, yes, I'm black and I'm proud of it. And that was my response at that time.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
The ethnic neighborhood was at the Akalyan Portugese.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:42.000
It was Italian, Greek. It was a mixture. Canadian, it was a mixture.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
How many were there, were there many blacks in your elementary school?

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:56.000
I know. I was the only black student when I went initially. And then it was a second. I still remember.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:03.000
She looked like an angel, Marilyn Miller came to school with a little pig dail.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So there was just the two of us, Lexington Avenue Elementary School.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:17.000
For a brief time in junior high school at Gilbert Stuart Junior High School, I was in a class with maybe four or five other black students.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:30.000
And then my mother arranged for me to go to an arranged a scholarship and everything at a local Quaker Prep School, Lincoln School for Girls.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:37.000
And I was the first year the only black student in the entire school which ran from preschool all the way through high school.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
Very exclusive school.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And then a young woman from Hampton, Virginia also came to the school in my sophomore year.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Who were your friends when you were growing up?

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:59.000
I made a couple of friends in the neighborhood.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:11.000
There was a family across the street from us. And actually the mother, years later, told me this very interesting story.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:20.000
She knew when we came, she told my children this story. She knew when we came to the community, you know, everybody was against it including her husband.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:26.000
And she tried to think of what kind of gesture could she do.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And so as soon as my father put his little sign out saying, you know, Dr. George Prescod, optometrist.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:41.000
She came to get her eyes examined. And he had put his office sort of at the front of the house.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
We divided the living room in half. So he had a little office.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:52.000
And she said while she was being examined, she realized he couldn't see that well.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.000
But she went ahead with it. He understood, you know, the gesture.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And so when the glasses came in, he told her there was no charge.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:10.000
And she told my children that she was still using the same prescription 40 years later.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
Well, that's a really nice story.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Well, you know, I was friends with her daughter. And there was a Canadian family, a little ways about a block away.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.000
And I got to know them quite well. And at one time I joined the Episcopal Church near us.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
And I was friends with the priest's daughter.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:37.000
And so those were my kind of local friends.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:45.000
What was Lincoln Christ School like?

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Of course, it was a, I said to say it was a wonderful educational experience.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:57.000
But it was to a certain point.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
I was not allowed to join the Glee Club.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And I believe it was because at that time the Girls Prep Schools Glee Club would have joint concerts with the Boys Prep School concerts.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:19.000
And they didn't want me socializing with the young men.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:26.000
Now when Carol came, she was such a phenomenal singer. She was also fair.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:36.000
She did join the Glee Club. You know, my freshman math teacher told me I was too dumb to learn that.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:42.000
It was an interesting experience from that point of view.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.000
I was very grateful to have you in the South when you were going up.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:54.000
When Emmett Till, you were just what two or three years younger?

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
And he was 15 at the time?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:57.000
I was 10.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:58.000
Oh, you were 10?

00:10:58.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I was 10.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Did that have an impact at all or on in the North?

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Of course, in the South movement people talk about that as sort of an iconic moment for them.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:17.000
It's very interesting that you should ask that because I was thinking about it this past week.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Because yes, many of the women who were hands in the Freedom Plow described themselves as children of the Emma Till generation.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:33.000
Emmett Till. My parents kept that from me until I was in college.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And in fact, what I think of is that I was a member of the Rosa Parks generation.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:54.000
Of course, because I was integrating schools, the whole process of school integration in the South resonated with me.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:02.000
And I kind of thought, you know, if they can go through that, well, I can deal with a little insults and problems that I have to deal with.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So I knew Daisy Bates and the Little Rock Nine, that's one of my earliest memories.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:19.000
And I had the image fixed in my mind of, because it was kindergarten students.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:25.000
It was elementary students, first graders, and college students integrating schools.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:30.000
And so that authoring Lucy, I remember.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:39.000
So it was more the activism that I remember from being a young child.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:45.000
And of course, one of the books, first books my mother gave me, the first books that I owned.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
We went to the library all the time, was Harriet Tubman. I think it was by Earl Conrad.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
That was the first one, book she gave me.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
Good coming off.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:05.000
So you did learn some Negro history, probably not in the schools, but your family?

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:11.000
Yes. A lot of it was musical. My mother actually sang opera.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:21.000
But she also sang spirituals. So, you know, I learned all the old spirituals to her.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And she contradicted not just black history.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:36.000
She taught me some black history, but she also taught me that the history that I was learning in school.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.000
The general history was off.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:49.000
I remember at one time, you know, when this middle of all this anti-communism and so forth, she said to me,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:56.000
oh, she said, they just, they're just mad because they can't sell anything over there in China.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:03.000
So it was, it was, it was both not trusting the history and the other thing that I remember about her is,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:09.000
she was a very serious church woman. She went to church every Sunday.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:15.000
You know, she did, she's played for churches and so forth. She's also an organist.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:21.000
But on the occasions when the ministers might start to talk about the role of women and so forth,

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:28.000
she would say, well, you know, Samantha Susan, it's Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
You don't see any women writing this, do you?

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
You know, take it with a grain of salt.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
Tell me about your church. Was it a black church?

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Oh, yeah.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Well, my parents went to Winter Street AME Zion Church.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.000
We remember that Winner Street was very small.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:59.000
The church was large. The church had been designed and built by a black architect, but the congregation had fallen off and was very small.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
I decided, you know, at some point that I wanted to be an Episcopalian.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And my parents said, well, you can go there, but you still have to go to Sunday school and you have to go to church with us as a family.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So I spent a lot of Sundays in church all day.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.000
It was a wonderful small congregation. Everybody knew everybody.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:32.000
And because my father couldn't see, I would sometimes accompany him to the trustee meetings and the other meetings.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And so I learned about basic meeting rules, order, and how things are handled, the finances, and so forth in an organization.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Well, it came time for you to go to college, Jen. You went to the University of Michigan.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:58.000
You said that that wasn't your first choice. Talk about the situation that led you to Ann Arbor.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:05.000
Well, my mother was a graduate of the University of Michigan.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:12.000
She graduated at 17, working her way through school.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:20.000
Because her father died at nine. And so she had to help support her family as well as go to high school in college.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:29.000
She determined that I should go to Michigan too. And this was what she could pay for.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:35.000
At that time, there weren't scholarships, kind of financially, that's available now.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:48.000
So she left Providence when I was a junior in high school, secured a job in Detroit, so that I would be certain to qualify for in-state tuition at the University of Michigan.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:49.000
You were in Providence in Providence?

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
Yes. My parents lived apart for two years.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:53.000
Because of you.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:17:00.000
So that I could go to the University of Michigan. And actually what they love this at Michigan, actually what she told me was,

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:07.000
you're going to the University of Michigan. And if you don't get in, you'll have to go to Michigan State.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Yeah, they wouldn't love that.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:18.000
So you ended up in Ann Arbor at a time when things were starting to happen politically there too.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.000
Tell us about your freshman year, your first year.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:27.000
Well, of course, I didn't expect anything. I wanted to go to Fisk.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:31.000
Because I had seen a white paper on the Nashville movement.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And my mother, of course, wouldn't hear about it.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:48.000
When I got to Ann Arbor, actually, trying to remain a good methodist that my parents had brought me up to be,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.000
I joined the Methodist Students Association on campus.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:56.000
And they had these Friday lunch and a brown bag events.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:02.000
And one of the early ones was they brought up two people from a coma, Mississippi.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And I remember meeting Curtis Hayes, who's now Curtis Hayes, Muhammad.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:14.000
They had a number of events that weekend. I followed them around to all the different events.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:25.000
Shortly after that, in that winter, Tom Hayden came back from Freedom Ride in Albany, Georgia.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:30.000
And so we learned about that. I joined SDS.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Students for Democratic.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Students for Democratic Society. Pretty much after I arrived on campus, they were the only organization talking about racism.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And what it meant was an all-white organization.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And peace. That was the other thing.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Were there many women in SDS at that time?

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
Yeah. I think it was pretty evenly divided.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
Men and women.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:12.000
And first, first, what I was doing was peace work.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:16.000
We had turned towards peace, I think that fall and so forth.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And when Hayden came back to campus, and of course he was an alumni too.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:26.000
So he was coming back to speak on this campus.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.000
And he had been editor of the Michigan Daily.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:37.000
He saw me in the office and he said, I don't, you know, why are you doing this peace work?

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:42.000
When your people are in motion all over the South.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:52.000
And so he invited a group of us to an SDS SNCC meeting in April of 1962 in Chapel Hill, North Carolina.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:20:00.000
And we, it was just so, I think it was Sharon Jeffrey, Mike Zweig, Kathy Innes, Dick Slee, and myself.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:07.000
We piled into this old car. We put five dollars in for gas each way.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:11.000
And we drove through the night to get there.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:17.000
And it was just an extraordinary experience once I was there, yeah.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
Who was there, you remember?

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:26.000
I think everybody in SNCC, who was not in jail, was there.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:32.000
My recollection is that everybody was there.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
And the same thing in SDS.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:38.000
And I often think how there were in this little chapel.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:44.000
It was maybe 50 people, maybe 75.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:53.000
And I think from that small group, there was the anti-war movement and the student civil rights movement.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:21:01.000
So with this in mind, after your freshman year, you decided you wanted to go south to work in a movement?

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
I did.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.000
I didn't cry at all.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:13.000
I didn't. I was 17 at the time and it was under the age of majority.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.000
And my parents were adamantly opposed.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.000
And so...

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:23.000
Did they tell you why?

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
That's very interesting. I don't think they ever said why.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
They just said, no.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:35.000
Well, they did talk about...

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:39.000
And this goes back to my mother's experience at University of Michigan.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:45.000
After she finished undergraduate school, she was admitted to the law school at Michigan.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:50.000
Along with, I think, about five other African-American students.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
She felt that they were admitted by a mistake.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:02.000
That because all of them had attended predominantly white schools, the law school didn't realize they were accepting black students.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:07.000
And within a year and a half, they figured a way to flunk them out.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:13.000
And she felt unfairly, you know, excluded.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:20.000
And so, her wish, of course, well, and I think this was pretty general at the time.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:25.000
Her wish, of course, was that I would go to law school or professional school.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:29.000
My father's wish was that I would be an ophthalmologist.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:38.000
But I think it was a general wish of black parents whose children got into these white majority white schools.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:42.000
We were a very small group.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.000
It was expected that you would become professional.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:51.000
That you would sort of keep your nose clean.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:57.000
We called it representing the race, which, of course, I have been doing from second grade or whatever.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
You know, you were supposed to be polite.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
Your clothes were supposed to be clean.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
And you were supposed to realize this.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:11.000
And it was. I mean, that you were given an incredible opportunity and that you should make the most of it.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:16.000
So I think that was the path that they had set me on.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:19.000
It was a path for which they had made tremendous sacrifices.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:22.000
I don't remember my mother was a musician.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:26.000
I don't remember her ever being able to attend a concert.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:35.000
Because any little extra money they had went to my, to what she had to pay for me to go to high school.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:43.000
They did without in order to be able to provide the education.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:49.000
So instead of going south, you enrolled at Wayne State for summer school?

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:54.000
That's exactly what I did the end of my in 1962, the summer of 1962.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.000
I enrolled at their insistence.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And of course, again, being very conscious of finances, my mother hoped that I would graduate in three years.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
You know, if you go to summer school.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:07.000
I think graduate at 17, why couldn't you?

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
Right, exactly.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.000
It was so nice growing up with my mother.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
My mother was able to read.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
You know, I'd come home with the pile of books, you know, from school.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
She'd read them the first week.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.000
She'd know what she would discuss with me.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:27.000
I was just like, but anyway, so I enrolled at Wayne State.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:33.000
I chose two courses by just guessing because they were early in the morning.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:38.000
And I ended up with two professors who were in facing reality.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:42.000
A group led by C.L.R. James.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:51.000
It was George Rawick who did a book on slavery, slave narratives, and Seymour Faber, who was a sociologist.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:59.000
And I picked him in the morning because by that time, Snicket sent Bernard Lafayette to Detroit to raise money.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:09.000
So I spent the mornings in these classes and the one, the favors class was a class on social change.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Rauwick's, if I remember correctly, was European history from 1848 to 1917.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:22.000
There was one revolution after another.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:35.000
And then in the afternoons, I worked with Bernard and the Friends of Snicket Group, Elizabeth Hirschfeld, who was a Freedom Rider, was the main other person.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:46.000
But also a lot of young people who had been active in civil rights in Detroit joined the Friends of Snicket Group.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And a good number of them later became active on campus.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:58.000
They took over the Newspaper Wayne State South End.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:12.000
And they were instrumental in the thing with James Forman and the Black Labor Group, I'll think of the name in a minute.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:25.000
So, and they were, it was John Watson and Luke Tripp, and they were already supporting the North Carolina, Robert F. Williams.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:34.000
And they were reading Negroes with guns, and they were getting the peaking review.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:39.000
They were very political. It was a very political group.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:49.000
And eventually we had people from a wide spectrum of the left, from the Catholic Worker.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:59.000
It was just a nice group of people. But there was work to do, and that's pretty much what we all did together.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:03.000
We just did support work for the students in the South.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:09.000
Then in the fall you went back to Michigan.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
I went back to Michigan.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And where was your mind that year, were you concentrating on your studies? Did you have a plan?

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:29.000
No, I'm not even sure how much I went to class. I think I spent most of my time in the student activities building.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:35.000
One of the things I want to mention that happened before I went, at that summer that we did the Friends of Snickwork,

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:43.000
at the end of the summer, our culminating event was bringing Diane Nash to Detroit.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:48.000
Who was very prominent in the SNCC and in this night program?

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:56.000
Yes. And at that time she was working in Mississippi. And she was under indictment in Mississippi.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:05.000
And her sort of tagline at the time was, yes, my baby might be born in jail, but anywhere a black child is in Mississippi.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:16.000
They're in jail already. But what I think was important to me as a young woman was that she was the star of the summer.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:26.000
Bernard Lafayette Jr is no mean speaker himself, but he chose to put her forward rather than himself.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:34.000
And the way he worked was very democratic. So I learned more about the SNCC way and so forth that summer.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:44.000
But to see her, she was nine months pregnant. She delivered, she left Michigan in labor.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:50.000
And it said a lot about what a woman could do in the movement to me.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:57.000
So I went back to school. I've set up a Friends of Snick group in Ann Arbor. We brought the Freedom Singers in.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:07.000
We did a variety of activities. I think it's that's 62, 63.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:19.000
I think it doesn't sound right. Okay, it was 62, 63. I planned to go south in 63 when I turned 18. But I didn't.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:26.000
My parents came to visit me in the fall of 1962 and they were back in Providence.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:36.000
No, they're in Detroit now. See, my mother has moved to Detroit. And they realized I had difficulty remembering exactly where my classes were located.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:43.000
And they said, you know, we're not paying you. We're not paying for you to sit in the student activities building.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:49.000
And I said, well, fine. You know, don't send me any more money. I'll manage on my own.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
The ubers of a kid.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:55.000
You're in the bed. Right.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:01.000
And that was the case. You know, from then on, I had to make arrangements for my own education.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:04.000
And then on the summer of 1963, you do head south.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:07.000
I do finally go south. And by your parents. Right.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:15.000
I kept hoping in the winter that I could convince them that it was okay.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:19.000
They made it clear that if I went, I would not be welcome to come back home again.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:29.000
And I didn't want that situation. But I did slip away at the end of the semester in 1963.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:33.000
And you ended up in Albany, Georgia. I did.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:36.000
With the project headed by Charles Sherrod. Yeah.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:40.000
You were there a brief time to talk about what it was like in Albany.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:47.000
Well, the first thing we did was we had orientation in Sumter County, Georgia.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:56.000
And that's where, again, the whole SNCC philosophy of following what the people wanted,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:01.000
not thinking of yourself as a leader, but as someone who can be of assistance,

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:09.000
and to listen to, to be guided by what community people wanted to have.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:17.000
Even Albany even was fairly frightening to me.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:21.000
I was scared the whole time I was there.

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Shortly after I arrived at orientation, a young woman, I believe, in Sumter County, Georgia,

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:37.000
was raped by 13 white men, one of whom was the, I think, the Sunbeam Bread route delivery driver.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:41.000
And he parked his truck in front of her house the whole time.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:45.000
She died from the infections and so forth that she received.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:56.000
And that, that was, it's just a huge eye-opener for me because I thought bad things happened,

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:00.000
but I thought the really bad things were over.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
And that wasn't the case.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:06.000
And I thought something like that could happen to me.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:11.000
I mean, that was even more frightening.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:21.000
The movement, they, I don't know, they say at the time that the movement was not what it had been before.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:26.000
I can only imagine what it had been before because we were still having huge mass meetings.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:33.000
And of course the music, the lining of the hymns and the music was just amazing.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
Was Brittany's rigging there? No, because the freedom singers were on.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:40.000
But it all started to take the matter.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:46.000
I mean, the music was just the line, Sharada's no mean singer either.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:50.000
You know, he would lead the mass meetings and so forth.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:57.000
And Rev. Samuel Wells was there and C.B. King was there.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:06.000
Going back to my parents, at one point, the, I felt kind of safe.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
I stayed within the black community.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:15.000
I felt like the real danger is when you started to march downtown, et cetera.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:18.000
So I was staying in the black community.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:23.000
And still, they came around, some of the police came around and arrested,

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.000
kept arresting people, arresting people.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:33.000
So Sharada had us take sanctuary in a church, which we did.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:39.000
But then I guess there were white men driving by with guns hanging out the window and so forth.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:51.000
And JoAnn Christian's father and her cousin, I think, Monroe, I'm losing his last name, but I'll come back with it.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:56.000
They sat on one side, one sat on the side of the church, church was on the corner under light,

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:00.000
one sat at the front of the church with a rifle across their laps,

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:07.000
which I think kept us from any severe reactions.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:12.000
But my mother heard about this through our severity.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:19.000
I think there were three women at the church who were deltas, myself, Joyce Ladner,

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:23.000
and Joan Browning, who'd been an exchange student.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:29.000
And so the deltas sent out this alarm and the head of the deltas at that time was from Albany, Georgia.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:36.000
Jeanne Noble. So my mother who was not speaking to me,

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:40.000
thrown me out of the family, got worried.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:46.000
And so she called an old high school friend of hers, Neil Staebler, who was a Democratic Committee.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:50.000
And he put her in touch with someone in the Justice Department.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:54.000
And she worked her way up to, this is, and she never told me this.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:58.000
Family members told me this story after she died.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:01.000
They've been sworn to secrecy.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:06.000
So the way they told it was, she finally got to Burke Marshall.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:08.000
It's a very general.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.000
Attorney General at the time.

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:13.000
And he passed her off to Robert Kennedy.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:19.000
And when she got to Robert Kennedy, Robert Kennedy assured her, she said,

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:23.000
I'll be sure that Noharn comes to your daughter, Mrs. Prescott.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.000
You don't have to worry about a thing.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.000
And she said, well, I hope so, young man,

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:32.000
because I would hate to have to talk to your brother about this.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.000
That's marvelous.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:38.000
And after that, I couldn't get arrested.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:43.000
I could just go anywhere.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:47.000
You could pose a poor point in the larger scheme of things.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:50.000
Okay, General, we're back.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:36:00.000
You have written that, although this was a non-violent movement that you engaged in what you call preventive non-violence.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
Talk about that.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:12.000
Well, I think my first exposure to this was in Albany, Georgia, where Charles Sherrod would let the gangs know when there was going to be a demonstration.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:22.000
And they would position themselves between the white crowd and the non-violent demonstrators.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.000
And of course, in these communities, everybody knew everybody.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:32.000
And so the people in the white crowd knew that there was this group of non-non-violent people.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:36.000
They had to go through to attack the demonstrators.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:40.000
And that kept the violence, I think, down.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:47.000
We didn't hesitate to ride in cars with community people who were armed,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:52.000
or to stay at the homes of community people who were armed.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:56.000
And I think, again, this protected us a great deal.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:06.000
I mean, the Mr. Christian and his cousin sitting on that porch, I think, kept people from shooting into the church.

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:09.000
It's just an amazing, brave thing to do.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:12.000
So you were protected by the local people?

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.000
Yes, very much so.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:20.000
And then soon you realized that Charles Sherrod had pulled a trick on you to keep you in Albany,

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
and you were really expected to agree what this is.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:33.000
Exactly. He told us that because Medgar Evers, it was too dangerous for us to go to Mississippi.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:42.000
But when we called over to Bob to find Moses, to Bob Moses, to just to say hello, he was waiting for us.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:50.000
So when Charles Sherrod was out of town, because we were afraid he would talk us and stay.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
Jean Wheeler, we were afraid he would talk us and stay.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:59.000
We got on a bus and went to Greenwood, Mississippi.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
I spent the rest of the summer.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.000
Well, Greenwood by that time had been in the national news.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:10.000
There had been demonstrations. The police had set dogs, loose on people.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:13.000
The Justice Department had gotten involved in a way.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:20.000
So taking that bus into Greenwood, what were your thoughts and what did you find when you got there?

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:24.000
Well, again, I was scared.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:30.000
And when we got there, I think Sam Block and Willie Peacock picked us up.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:34.000
They had a car. It was like a bumblebee. It was yellow and black.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:40.000
And when they picked us up, they must have driven through Greenwood at 80 miles an hour.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:45.000
So then I had another thing. Was I even going to make it to the office?

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:51.000
You were in Washington Peacock where the original two-snake people who went into Greenwood.

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:54.000
Yes. So you were being met by the people who started though.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:39:00.000
Yes. Yes. And, you know, of course they were heroes to us and so forth.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:09.000
And that summer, we were working on getting people to the polls and groups.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:17.000
And large numbers, having voting days, having a voting day, rather than taking two or three people down at a time and so forth.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:32.000
And so my job was really to get familiar with the community and said I had learned this working with SDS and Democratic Party and, you know, setting up how

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:38.000
which homes had already been called on, which ones hadn't so forth.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:42.000
So there were still a lot of attempts made to register.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:49.000
Yes. We had a voting day at the end of the summer is what I remember with two or three hundred people.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:52.000
How many of them were successful do you think?

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:54.000
Oh, I don't think anybody was successful.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:57.000
That they were using all of the devices they could.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
They just didn't register.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
Interpreting the Constitution.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:04.000
I actually never went inside.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:08.000
So I don't know what happened once people went inside.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:13.000
But I know that nobody got registered. I mean, for the most part, nobody got registered.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:19.000
But they were so brave to keep coming back and attempting to register.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:27.000
People, again, people were driving by white men were driving by the office with their guns out and so forth.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:30.000
Contrast, comparing contrast, will you?

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:33.000
I've been interested in this.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:41.000
The way Charles Sherrod was running the Albany Project and the way the things were being run in Greenwood.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:46.000
Well, Mrs. Cippy was...

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:56.000
Charles Sherrod's project... there were white volunteers in Albany.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:04.000
There were a couple of white volunteers in Mississippi, two men, but they never left the office.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:07.000
It was too dangerous.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:09.000
Dangerous for them and for the community.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:19.000
Yes. So they actually lived, bathed, ate, everything in that office.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:26.000
I would say that for me, and this was part of what attracted me to this movement,

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:37.000
they were both black projects because the movement itself was black.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:43.000
When I was in Albany going to mass meetings, you know, there are 700 people in the church.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:48.000
Maybe there are 10 white volunteers there.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.000
I'm not sure that's integrated.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:42:00.000
You know, where integrated to me is more of a 50-50 kind of a situation.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:03.000
The culture of the movement was black.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.000
Charles Sherrod was in charge.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:15.000
There wasn't a situation where he was sharing with a white person to run the project when he left Prathia Hall, took over.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:21.000
So for me, there wasn't that much difference.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:24.000
But again, this is what attracted me to him.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:31.000
What I saw in Chapel Hill were young black people in charge, taking charge of their destiny.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.000
That's what attracted me.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:36.000
We could do something about our own situation.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:39.000
We could actually change things.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:50.000
So in Mississippi, it's pretty much the same as far as I felt it, as I experienced.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:57.000
So you were happy to be in a black-run, black project.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:58.000
Yes.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:05.000
You were a woman in that movement, and a lot has been written in recent years about the role of women in the movement.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:10.000
The mistreatment, the alleged mistreatment of women, what was your experience?

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.000
I certainly never felt mistreated.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:21.000
And I felt encouraged to be as much as I could be.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:27.000
I felt myself a novice in these situations.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:36.000
I mean, I had never been in a, what was I guess, a war zone to me before.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:44.000
So I was feeling my way in learning, but I felt encouraged to do as much as the men were doing.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
Or as just as much as I could do.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
We were college students.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:53.000
So certainly, we retreated as if we were smart.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:44:04.000
So you know, I never felt that someone looked down on me through that experience.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:10.000
Did women have roles they were expected to perform?

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:11.000
Not that I was aware of.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:14.000
They did some medicine meetings and things like this.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:18.000
I don't remember anybody taking minutes to the meetings I was.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:21.000
Somebody did because I was really a lot of people.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:25.000
But one of the things I noticed was that in reading the medicine meeting,

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:30.000
you would have an age of people who were talking, but if you didn't, you wouldn't know which gender was.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:35.000
Even nobody was putting down somebody because of their gender.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:38.000
But that's something, of course, that's been out there.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:43.000
So you were in 63 things are going in Mississippi, and then what did you do in the fall?

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:47.000
In the fall, we went to the march on Washington.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:51.000
And I went home to try to reconcile with my parents.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:53.000
Talk a little bit about the march on Washington.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:57.000
Was that a great experience for you?

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:01.000
Actually, the march on Washington, after being in Mississippi,

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:07.000
it seemed kind of too civilized or something.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
Sort of toned down.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
You were with the SNCC people who were there.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.000
From Mississippi, yeah.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:19.000
And I remember my identification was with the people coming in Jeans from Danville,

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.000
and the people coming from Cambridge, Maryland,

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:26.000
where they had had a hard fought summer.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:29.000
They did have seats for us for Mississippi.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
We got to sit at the front.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:38.000
So, you know, like in the Democratic Convention, you were honored guests.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:43.000
So, that we, you know, we picketed the Justice Department the night before,

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:48.000
and then we came to the march.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:58.000
Of course, the numbers of people there were just so impressive.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:02.000
But I think the, you know, reaction to Jeans proposed speech.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:05.000
This is Jeann Lewis, who had a speech censor.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:10.000
Yes, the fact that the speech was censored.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:19.000
I remember being slightly conscious that there weren't that many women speaking on the program.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:34.000
And just at that point, I felt like a soldier in the civil rights army.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:41.000
The other thing that disturbed me, I, W.E.B. Du Bois died on that day.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:49.000
And Roy Wilkins, head of the NAACP, made actually a disparaging remark.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
I don't remember what it was.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:54.000
Well, I felt he made a disparaging remark about the boys.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:58.000
And I thought it was just, how could you be so cheap with someone?

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.000
Still holding a grudge.

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:04.000
And that, that's my recollection of the march.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:09.000
So then you went back to say to try to reconcile with my parents.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:16.000
And I carefully went back after, I did some fundraising first in Massachusetts.

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:19.000
And then I went back to try to reconcile with my parents.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:24.000
And I carefully went back after classes started at University of Michigan.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:29.000
But what my mother knew was that classes had not started at Wayne.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:40.000
And she faked the heart attack to keep me at home.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:50.000
And years later, years later, I asked her, you know, how could she have done that?

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:56.000
And she said, I would have done anything to keep you out of Mississippi.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:48:03.000
And when I was, you know, working on the bridges for hands,

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:11.000
and particularly reading your book, the level of violence in Mississippi in those years was incredible.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
It was absolutely incredible.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:19.000
I got chills all over again, thinking of how dangerous it actually was.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:26.000
You were aware of that at the time that it didn't deter you at all.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:31.000
I was a, no, I wasn't.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:34.000
I knew, I was risking my life.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:38.000
I knew it was dangerous.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:45.000
I did not know that the clan or the White Assistance Council had a list of people

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:48.000
that they had successfully murdered.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:53.000
I knew people were dying.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:00.000
But I think I was not, just, I think it was neither aware of the level of violence,

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:04.000
nor later of the level of surveillance.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:11.000
You know, we joked about it, but I didn't think it was, yeah, the surveillance was that great.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:15.000
So you were up north at Wayne State, and then you...

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.000
I can't ask you a question.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:23.000
You referred to John Lewis being censored, and I probably just come up several times.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:27.000
Could you just say why he was censored, or what he was censored about?

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:33.000
I think they felt the speech was too radical.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:40.000
And if I remember correctly, he had something in there about marching through the South like Sherman,

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:43.000
nonviolently.

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:46.000
That didn't go over.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:57.000
But again, it's this polite, this, the march is on a different level than the level on which we were working.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:58.000
I felt.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:06.000
And one of the things I think was that the march was turned around to be an endorsement of Kennedy Civil Rights Bill.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:10.000
And in that first draft of the speech, he said it's too little and too late.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:13.000
And that was a no-no.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:23.000
I think several people would have dropped out if he would have done it, so a compromise was maybe still strong speech.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:28.000
But they had distributed copies in advance, so the rest knew exactly what it was.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:32.000
Well, I think he asked, I want to know what side the federal government is.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:39.000
And that was not acceptable at the time either.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:51.000
And I think it was more the traditional groups, not necessarily SCLC, but...

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:57.000
So, you're up north in the summer in 1964.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:51:05.000
The summer of 1964 was the time of the summer project, later known as Freedom Summer in Mississippi.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:13.000
Three civil rights workers being killed, national and international attention.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:17.000
Why didn't you go back to Mississippi that summer?

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:20.000
Well, two reasons.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:24.000
I actually was opposed to the summer project.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.000
A number of SNCC fields after territory.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:27.000
Why were you?

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:28.000
Many.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:31.000
I think the whole Mississippi staff almost said that.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:34.000
Except all the voices.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:44.000
Because again, I felt that the idea of having black student organizers and the black community in the sound,

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:50.000
so that it was sound, it worked.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:56.000
And so when I realized they weren't recruiting black students, I was discouraged.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:02.000
And the second thing was I figured out if I went to summer school in 1964,

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:07.000
I could finish school that following fall.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:13.000
And again, you know, that would just be checking off one objection in my parents' head.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:14.000
Yes.

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:26.000
But you did go to Atlantic City in August when the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party challenged the legitimacy of the all white Mississippi delegation.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:27.000
What was that like?

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:29.000
What was your role there?

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:35.000
I did go and even previous to that, I did some work with Detroit friends at SNCC,

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:42.000
because the Michigan Democratic Party was the first party to support the MFDP.

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:47.000
So we were all proud of that.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:53:00.000
I went, I went, I was at that meeting where, you know, first we were just generally demonstrating on the boardwalk.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:13.000
And I went to the meeting where people came to talk to the Mississippi Democratic delegation to ask them to support,

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:22.000
to encourage them to support the two seats, the offer of the two seats.

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:31.000
And I remember Mrs. Hamer getting up when it was over.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:41.000
I remember two or three things. One was, I think, a gentleman from the Council of Churches was so embarrassed by the position that he was taking.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:52.000
He looked down, he was read in the face and looked down through the whole time that he was making his presentation.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:56.000
And then, you know, Mrs. Hamer got up and basically said, I know what democracy is.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:01.000
First of all, we should get to choose who our representatives are.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:07.000
They had appointed Johnson administration and appointed Ed King (Edwin King, MFDP minister) and Aaron Henry and Aaron Henry.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:13.000
And so, and the vote went with her.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:17.000
And I thought it was a wonderful victory.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.000
Yeah. Yeah. I thought it was a one.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:26.000
I thought, and it's not just about this specific event.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:36.000
I thought it was absolutely amazing that within the space of what is at two years of activism,

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:45.000
with basically no money, we had made the vote a national issue.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:50.000
It was on the national agenda. It wasn't going anywhere after that.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:55.000
And to me, it's the whole movement was like that.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:55:01.000
That given the opposition against us, given that there was, I felt only this,

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:06.000
there was just this small historical opening to make change.

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.000
We blew it wide open.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:15.000
And so, in that sense, I always felt encouraged.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:24.000
I felt as if we were, you know, there's a point in Chicago where there's a mass meeting,

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:29.000
I think after they've gone into Cicero, Illinois and the rocks are coming down and everything.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:33.000
And the Mahalia Jackson sings before King speaks.

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:38.000
And she sings Joshua Fit the Battle of Jericho" and the walls came tumbling down".

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:44.000
And that just to me was such the perfect image.

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:53.000
I felt not that we were sort of marching around the walls of racial oppression or segregation with horns,

00:55:53.000 --> 00:56:00.000
but we were leaning on it. And it was tumbling down. And it did.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:02.000
Yeah.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:05.000
Okay, we're rolling. John, can you back up this?

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:10.000
Okay, we're going to go.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.000
Oh, I'm a fan of you.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.000
We're attending the University of Michigan.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:22.000
And you made most of your credits for graduation at the end of the fall semester of 1964.

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:27.000
And then early in 1965, you joined the Alabama SNCC project.

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:32.000
Talk a little bit about that. What was going on? What you found there?

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:39.000
Well, at first, when I went to the Alabama SNCC project, I was going on the weekends because during the week,

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:45.000
I was long weekends. I was also working on the project with Pat Gurin from the University of Michigan,

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:51.000
studying the vocational aspirations of students at Black colleges.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:55.000
And one of the colleges was Tuskegee.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:59.000
So in that process, we got to know a lot of the activist students.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:03.000
And another SNCC person, Doris A. Derby, was on that study.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:10.000
And another historian, John H. Bracey Jr, was also one of the interviewers.

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:18.000
So we got to know the students at Tuskegee, the activist students, and they were having mass meetings.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:31.000
And they actually tended to get together around 11 or 12 o'clock in the daytime and kind of socialize the rest of the day.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:39.000
In Selma, when I worked in Selma, I worked in a ward of Selma. I was assigned a ward.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:46.000
And we did in Selma, whatever the people coming to the meeting wanted us to do.

00:57:46.000 --> 00:58:00.000
It could be something as simple as getting a stoplight on a corner, or as complicated as trying to get Black women hired at the Dan River Mills.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:11.000
Which of course paid more. I think the thing that struck me in Selma, and Mississippi was probably a little bit less.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:24.000
And Selma, the going wage for day work, was $12 a week for a six-day week.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:29.000
So we were at the Dan River Mills.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
Did you have any success there?

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:37.000
I believe the women got hired. That's my memory. I'm not sure of it.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:51.000
So we were doing sort of economic projects. We also, I was working with people in another ward where the men working at the Pepsi plant wanted to unionize.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:59:02.000
And we worked with an organizer from the AFL-CIO who came in at night. The meetings had to be at night. He had to park.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:10.000
Nobody parked all in front of the house. So that was the trade union organizing.

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:19.000
And we were still taking people, going with people to register to vote.

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:27.000
Later on, we challenged the assignment of the poverty funds to the mayor and so forth.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:41.000
It was about this time, early in 1965, that Martin Luther King and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, came to Selma with the intent of dramatizing something that the Civil Rights Act of 60 who were didn't cover.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:50.000
And that was the right to vote. They came to Selma to make a big splash, put pressure on Congress to pass the law.

00:59:50.000 --> 01:00:01.000
Snick had been working quietly in the community for a couple of years. Talk a little bit about that dynamic when SCLC came and how things changed or didn't.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:16.000
You know, I think too, and maybe this is a little off the subject. My firm belief, and I don't know if this again will be proven when things are, all the records are open and so forth.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:30.000
I suspect that after the MFDP challenge and the kinds of people that the MFDP represented, somebody said,

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:46.000
you know, we can't let this radical SNCC organization create a populist party in the South.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:53.000
And you guys in SCLC should do something about this.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:01:08.000
I do know that in the fall of 1964, there was a meeting held in New York with Allard Lowenstein and lots of other liberals, the intent of which was to make sure that FDP did not get support.

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:29.000
And there is also a document from an SCLC meeting about kind of taking up the issue of the vote and being in the middle of SNCC projects in Mississippi and Georgia.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:45.000
So anyway, we were not, well, I remember in particular, we weren't like overboard about SCLC coming into Alabama, which had a SNCC presence.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:49.000
I don't think Lafayette was there in 1961.

01:01:49.000 --> 01:02:01.000
So at the same time, it's not like there was hostility.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:10.000
We all ate together at the Walker's Cafe, you know, we're certainly talking with each other.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:11.000
I mean, it wasn't...

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:13.000
You have to know King there, though.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:16.000
I just met him a couple times. I think Andrew Young was there more.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:23.000
We got to know him. He was in and out, but Andy was there a lot.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:32.000
At that point, Diane and James Bevel were working for SCLC. So you know, certainly friends with them.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:48.000
And so it was a kind of an interesting arrangement. And actually in the awards in Selma, there was a SNCC person assigned to each award and an SCLC person assigned to each award as an attempt to kind of work together through this.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:56.000
But they tended to be promoting demonstrations and, you know, we were community organizers.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:04.000
And so we were doing more... actually kind of local groundwork, kind of things, I think.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:18.000
The world became aware of Selma Gridge when police attacked demonstrators, tear gas clubs.

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Talk about that and the impact that it had on SNCC and what it was doing at the time.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:34.000
Well, even though at the time SNCC had taken an official position against supporting the March to Montgomery.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:48.000
And so, although there were SNCC individuals like John Lewis, Bob Mants participating in the March, after bloody Sunday, you know, everybody came to Selma.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:57.000
And the SNCC staff in Selma that had not been participating in the March also participated in the next March.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:01.000
Which we call the U-turn March.

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:02.000
What is the U-turn March?

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:09.000
Because basically, you know, everybody was all revved up and they were ready to go across that bridge and to go through anything.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:21.000
And when they got to the bridge, the leadership, the SCLC leadership stopped, said, let us pray and led the March back to Brown's chapel.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:24.000
So it was a very disciplined...

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:27.000
We did that probably because the deal was made.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Yeah.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:32.000
They wouldn't be attacked as long as they turned around and came back.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:40.000
After that, why there was a federal permission to March.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:49.000
And so the March from Selma to Montgomery got underway and was completed. Were you on that March?

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:53.000
I didn't actually go on the March.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:55.000
And I'm just going to go back to a second.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:06.000
There's a very interesting story in the Hands on the Freedom Plow: Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC: Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC written by Fay Bellamy Powell, where she describes going with, I think,

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:21.000
James Forman and Stokely to a dentist's house in Selma the night before this March, where James Forman and Stokely were pleading with King to go against his principles and break the federal injunction.

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:30.000
But the thing that was interesting was they knew where he was. They came in the middle of the night and he got up and met with them.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:34.000
But he was also on the phone in the other room with the federal.

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:36.000
They kind of did a go. Roll.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:39.000
Yes. I kind of feel sorry for him.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:43.000
But so now I'm forgetting your question.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:47.000
Well, no, you did not go on the March.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:54.000
I did not go on the March, but I did go into, well, there were two things.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:06:01.000
So also at the same, what snick did at the same time was have demonstrations in Montgomery.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:10.000
So I did go and watch the demonstrations in Montgomery because students from the University of Michigan came down.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:16.000
There was some kind of relationship between Tuskegee and the University of Michigan and institutional relationship between the two schools.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:19.000
So you were in Montgomery then with all the departments there?

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:26.000
I was in Montgomery. I left when I knew things were going to get rough.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:30.000
Because again, we had taken the position that we were no longer demonstrators.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:36.000
We were community organizers and we were going to focus on that community organization.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:44.000
Now I did go into Montgomery on the day the March culminated.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:47.000
What were your feelings?

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:52.000
It was sort of whole home.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:56.000
You know, we expected it to happen.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:03.000
We knew and we were at the church.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:06.000
It's right on the corner by the Capitol.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:10.000
So we could hear the speeches and we were feeding people.

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:13.000
Was that changed church?

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:18.000
I believe so. I want to call it Ebenezer and that's why I know I'm wrong.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:21.000
It's Dexter Avenue King Memorial Baptist Church.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:25.000
It was the president of the president of the Capitol.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:39.000
And it was what I thought was beautiful was to see how many community people were participating in that March.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:42.000
Because the streets of Montgomery were full.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:45.000
It was a point where we couldn't drive anymore.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:49.000
We had to park the car and walk the rest of the way.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:52.000
So for it.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:59.000
And then the March ended and the press went away and you went back to work.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:06.000
Right. And I think that our concern was even in what was proposed in a voting rights bill.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:17.000
I didn't offer any protection for people who were trying to register to vote and for workers, for voter workers.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:27.000
And so I remember kind of being like, well, another bill won't protect us, won't protect people.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:35.000
Well, I want to second I want you to talk about what it was like registering people in that area once the voting rights act was passed.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:44.000
But it was at this time that Stokely Carmichael was going off from the March and organizing people in Lowndes County, Alabama.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:50.000
Alabama, which became the Lowndes County, Alabama Freedom Organization, the first Black Panther Party.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:54.000
You have changes going on and SNCC.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:09:02.000
And you were continuing to be active in Alabama and not much has been written or said about that.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:08.000
I wish you could go into detail. I believe the Medical Committee for Human Rights had a project there.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:11.000
What were you doing after the March?

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:16.000
After the March, we were still canvassing.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:21.000
The thing that I remember was people were going down to register and drove.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:29.000
And I was making some attempt, we had these sheets of people who had gone to register, et cetera.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:42.000
And I was making some attempt, which I never did finish, of trying to organize them by awards so that we would have the information of who was registered, who wasn't.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:52.000
Now it became more of an administrative kind of thing because they sent in federal registrars.

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:55.000
So people weren't having any difficulty getting registered.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:09:57.000
So the matter of motivating them to get out and register?

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:00.000
Well, people were going in droves. We didn't have to do anything.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:07.000
They were just going in droves. But the thing in Selmer is we were thinking, okay, now there's going to be elections.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:15.000
Can we start organizing? But by that time, everybody was pretty much out in the counties.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:25.000
And as you say, the focus was on Lowndes County, Alabama and the idea of an independent black political party.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:30.000
And that's where SNCC's efforts went at that time.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:32.000
Did you work in Lounds at all?

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:40.000
I visited Lounds. I was there, I think, for the first mass meeting.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:52.000
And I thought it was interesting that people, you know, as soon as that meeting was over, the people in Lowndes County, Alabama had a set arrangement about how they were getting home so no one would be endangered.

01:10:52.000 --> 01:10:55.000
It's like, oh, we've done this before.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:05.000
You know, but I didn't, and I spent, I think I spent a couple of weeks there when I came back to Alabama.

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:10.000
I went home for a little while and came back to Alabama. But it was not.

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:16.000
My Selmer was my permanent place. I was at the meeting.

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:30.000
We were at a Boy Scout camp, I think. We had a meeting where the whole discussion was about the formation of an independent black political party and the black Panther.

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:40.000
I, of course, wasn't so hot on the Panther. I wanted a black star, but that was...

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:48.000
I don't even remember if I had the nerve to say anything about it.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:54.000
But I actually believe in nonviolent direct action.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:01.000
And I thought the Panther was a little over the top.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:12.000
And I liked something that would have connected it to the African struggle, which I think a black star would have done.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:16.000
What do you think the six playing with the black star is?

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:29.000
Marcus Garvey had the black star line, the steamship line, it's a symbol, and then in Krumah, I picked it up.

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:41.000
I think for the airlines, for the Ghanaian Airlines. So, you know, this is in the back of my mind, say, compared to a black Panther.

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:47.000
I just worked with St. Robert in Jamaica, across the Far East, and of course, Marcus Garvey.

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:58.000
Yes. My father always referred to him as the honorable Marcus Garvey.

01:12:58.000 --> 01:13:22.000
And I also think I remember I did not have the same understanding about the importance of black institutions as some of my SNCC colleagues at that time.

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:31.000
I thought it didn't make a difference if you had a Lowndes County, Alabama Freedom Organization.

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:39.000
And that organization wanted to field independent candidates one year, Democratic candidates another year.

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:42.000
I thought it was all fine.

01:13:42.000 --> 01:13:55.000
But that shows my separation from the thinking of the time. I was not representative at all.

01:13:55.000 --> 01:14:15.000
When you were in Alabama in the ensuing months in 1965, what was, you had the all the attention and sound, what were race relations like in the period after the March until you left?

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:21.000
Did things improve at all, did they get worse? Did they stay the same?

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:29.000
Well, one of the interesting things was when we challenged the poverty funds, the mayor started meeting with us.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:32.000
Mayor (Joseph T.) Smitherman of Selma.

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:44.000
He was very cordial and pleasant. And of course, was there a cat board of community action program board there that was in charge of all that?

01:14:44.000 --> 01:14:57.000
All I remember was that the mayor was in charge of the poverty funds. And we held several mass meetings to have the community support to challenge it.

01:14:57.000 --> 01:15:05.000
But I left actually before that whole process was finished. And I don't know what happened.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:13.000
And I was actually working with a woman from SCLC. I didn't surely, Mercer, I think her name was.

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:31.000
But I know that there was a quick response. It was just immediate. While we were there, even during the movement, I think we were able to, they talked to us, the Selma officials.

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:45.000
It was kind of funny. The SNCC office was directly across the street from the police station. And we could actually see people in jail through our window.

01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:49.000
So this is very physically close proximity.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:58.000
Very different from the image we get of the police in Selma because all we have is pictures of pushing back and beating.

01:15:58.000 --> 01:16:03.000
But there wasn't any communication at all. Well, it's the state troopers, which is kind of interesting.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:14.000
Because everybody thought the state was more liberal than Selma. But it's the state troopers who are beating people on Edmund Pettus Bridge.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:19.000
And you mentioned Wilson Baker, director of public safety, as somebody you could talk to.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:27.000
Well, I had his phone. I don't know how I got it. I had his phone number at home and in the office.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:34.000
And I can't even remember, did he walk up to me one day and say, well, you don't if you ever need me.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:42.000
I don't know. But I did call him one night when we went to a restaurant on Halloween, which wasn't smart.

01:16:42.000 --> 01:16:47.000
And you know, it looked like people were going to try to hurt us. He sent a car.

01:16:47.000 --> 01:16:51.000
A couple police cars take us home.

01:16:51.000 --> 01:16:58.000
I have worth told me stories about the police station being across from the office.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:01.000
Was that all you said before you got there?

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:02.000
Yeah.

01:17:02.000 --> 01:17:08.000
He says he said he set that up. And so that when he went out into the field, he could talk to people and say,

01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:13.000
well, you know where my office is. And they don't have to laugh.

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:17.000
Because I think he was there in that early group.

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:23.000
He came early. So that was, yeah, that was all set up before we got there.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:30.000
When you were in Alabama this time, you also had an active social life.

01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:31.000
Well, kind of.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:32.000
I'm talking about it.

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:38.000
I didn't. I didn't. I didn't. I didn't. I didn't meet my first husband there. Yes.

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:41.000
He was the project.

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:50.000
And you were married when we married in the fall of 1967.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:54.000
And he had orders to Vietnam.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:58.000
And he was on that break.

01:17:58.000 --> 01:18:05.000
They give you like I think a 30 day or maybe it might even been a 60 day break before you actually transfer over.

01:18:05.000 --> 01:18:11.000
He had applied to be for CO standing before he was drafted and they didn't give it to him.

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:17.000
But he learned while he was in the army. He kept going to different schools to avoid going to Vietnam.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:23.000
And then he learned while he was in the army that in that space,

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:28.000
you're no longer under the chain of command. And you go straight to the top.

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:31.000
And that's what he did. And he was an officer.

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:41.000
And as an officer, the burden of proof of your being a CO is now on the army, not on you.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:43.000
It's just the opposite if you're an enlisted man.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:48.000
Because obviously they don't want a pacifist in charter troops.

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:55.000
And so he was successful in doing that.

01:18:55.000 --> 01:19:01.000
I had told him after he proposed and I knew this was hanging over him.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:06.000
I said, you know, well, if you go to Canada, I'll go with you.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:09.000
If you go to Africa, I'll go with you.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:12.000
If you go to jail, I'll wait for you.

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:17.000
He said, my mother took him aside and said, young man,

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:24.000
you are not taking my daughter anywhere where I have to cross an international boundary to see her.

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:30.000
And if you go to jail, I'll be tempted to shoot you before you get out of the courtroom.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:35.000
Because my daughter will not be married to a felon.

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:38.000
Have you and your parents been reconciled by them?

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:42.000
We were... I was living at home.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:45.000
We weren't reconciled.

01:19:45.000 --> 01:19:55.000
Again, I believe my mother insisted that I be allowed back at home against my father's wishes.

01:19:55.000 --> 01:20:03.000
And so there was still a lot of tension that really didn't dissipate until shortly before my mother died.

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:08.000
Did you and her dad grow around Wayne State in the summer of 1966?

01:20:08.000 --> 01:20:10.000
I did.

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:14.000
I was I met Silas (Norman) — speaker mid-sentence. We're married in 1967.

01:20:14.000 --> 01:20:17.000
You had a baby, a small son.

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:19.000
And you decided to go back to Albany.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:23.000
We did. We sheried by that time, was doing farming.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:28.000
We had a huge community. I think it was a size of New York City.

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:32.000
It was this huge plot of land called New Communities Inc Inc.

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:36.000
And we discussed, you know, going to work with him.

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:40.000
And we went down there to visit and he took us around.

01:20:40.000 --> 01:20:43.000
And he took us to the house and here and there.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:46.000
And the house was all shot up in the back.

01:20:46.000 --> 01:20:50.000
It was just sort of a matter of fact, you know, as well.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:59.000
And I thought we didn't really have the right to risk the baby's life.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:04.000
And we both thought we should have more education.

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:06.000
And so Silas Norman Jr Jr Norman went to medical school.

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:15.000
And after we had two more children, I went to back to school

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:18.000
and entered a PhD program in history, yeah.

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:24.000
In 1967, you were down and then you went back.

01:21:24.000 --> 01:21:27.000
Changes were taking place in Snick.

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:37.000
Talk about how you fit into the discussions, how you fit into the changes in direction in Snick.

01:21:37.000 --> 01:21:42.000
You know, unfortunately, I had a habit of going to Snick meetings,

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:45.000
but not actually going to the meeting.

01:21:45.000 --> 01:21:48.000
I would stay outside to meet.

01:21:48.000 --> 01:21:50.000
What, why didn't you go inside?

01:21:50.000 --> 01:21:55.000
I'd like to meet with people from other projects, find out what they were doing,

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:59.000
and that kind of thing.

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:02.000
I mean, I would go in and out.

01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:06.000
There's a lot of tension in those meetings and those things.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:10.000
I didn't take it as seriously probably as I should have,

01:22:10.000 --> 01:22:16.000
because I thought that we had our marching orders, so to speak.

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:19.000
We had misspeckers. We had a philosophy.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:24.000
And to me, the discussions that were taking place were within that context.

01:22:24.000 --> 01:22:30.000
And I believed to this day easily, resolvable.

01:22:30.000 --> 01:22:37.000
But again, I was someone who was there in the beginning,

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:42.000
or close to the beginning, and saw Snick as a black organization.

01:22:42.000 --> 01:22:48.000
And I saw the Mississippi Summer Project as the aberration.

01:22:48.000 --> 01:22:54.000
And what happened afterwards as a return to where it started.

01:22:54.000 --> 01:22:58.000
So I wasn't going, oh, this is something new.

01:22:58.000 --> 01:23:01.000
It was going like, oh, this is something old.

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:06.000
And it's actually something that Stokely Carmichael says in the black power.

01:23:06.000 --> 01:23:12.000
We were trying to build vehicles of black power from the beginning.

01:23:12.000 --> 01:23:16.000
So when the black power slogan came out, you were not surprised.

01:23:16.000 --> 01:23:18.000
No. Turned off, or?

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:20.000
No. I thought.

01:23:20.000 --> 01:23:25.000
So what we were doing all along was building vehicles of black power.

01:23:25.000 --> 01:23:32.000
And interestingly enough, one of the, my parents' objections was

01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:37.000
to the integrated nature of the Friends of Snick,

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:44.000
because we actually had a party at my house in Detroit

01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:47.000
after Stokely Carmichael gave up black power speech.

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:52.000
And I swear, my mother said to Stokely Carmichael when he came in the house,

01:23:52.000 --> 01:23:57.000
oh, young man, I'm so glad you all finally got some sense.

01:23:57.000 --> 01:24:01.000
And now what you need to do is organize, organize, organize.

01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:05.000
Which of course was in slow-pin' with there.

01:24:05.000 --> 01:24:08.000
She loved black power.

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:10.000
Oh, yeah.

01:24:10.000 --> 01:24:14.000
No, no, it just seemed to me the same.

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:19.000
But I think, of course, the people who had come in either in the summer of 1964

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:26.000
or afterwards saw the early Snick as a quote, integrationist organization.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:30.000
Which I didn't understand that.

01:24:30.000 --> 01:24:38.000
And I didn't feel that what we were trying to do was to integrate into white society.

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:44.000
I never had that feeling either that I thought what we were trying to do was build these vehicles of black power.

01:24:44.000 --> 01:24:53.000
And to radicalize the entire political structure of the country.

01:24:53.000 --> 01:25:02.000
Because the, what, what oppressed black people in the south would want

01:25:02.000 --> 01:25:12.000
and would lobby for, would be so much more liberal and radical than any other group of people in the country.

01:25:12.000 --> 01:25:15.000
That was my understanding of what we were doing.

01:25:15.000 --> 01:25:22.000
And so I didn't see, I didn't see this big change.

01:25:22.000 --> 01:25:26.000
What did you, what do you want to do?

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:41.000
The other thing that was so clear was that we were still talking about a movement based in the black community.

01:25:41.000 --> 01:25:49.000
There was a brief talk about, you know, there were these white projects in Mississippi.

01:25:49.000 --> 01:26:00.000
But there really wasn't any discussion about building a black and white southern movement together.

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:15.000
I do think one of the opportunities that we missed because of these discussions in the meeting was bringing the southern movements together.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:30.000
So creating at least a meeting of the Southwest Georgia, the Mississippi, the Cambridge movement, bringing these projects together and developing a platform.

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:35.000
Well, this time there was more activity in cities in the North.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:38.000
And you were, you and your husband and your family were in Detroit.

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:39.000
Yes.

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:45.000
You went back to graduate school in history at the University of Michigan.

01:26:45.000 --> 01:26:51.000
Briefly tell us about what you've been up to the last 45 years.

01:26:51.000 --> 01:26:57.000
I think a combination of studying history, teaching history.

01:26:57.000 --> 01:27:05.000
I didn't finish my, the PhD program because of a series of family emergencies.

01:27:05.000 --> 01:27:08.000
I raised a family. I took care of my parents.

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:22.000
And I've done a number of community projects like an anti-hunger project, a program for children, a tutorial program for children with sickle cell andemia.

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:45.000
And I stayed active with a number of what I would call post-snick projects, helping to organize some retrospective conferences about SNCC, helping to get Curtis, Hayes, out of jail in Liberia.

01:27:45.000 --> 01:27:46.000
Things like that.

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:51.000
And tell us about your family.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:28:00.000
Well, I have three wonderful sons who we raised in the city of Detroit, in the inner city of Detroit.

01:28:00.000 --> 01:28:18.000
And so they and we have experienced, I guess what I would call a new set of dangers, in terms of attacks and arrests by police.

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:29.000
And the level of violence that's now, I think, within the black community.

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:38.000
My son was a pallbearer, two weeks after he graduated from high school.

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:48.000
And within my little circle of friends in Detroit, at least four women have lost their sons to gun violence.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:54.000
It became a pro forma.

01:28:54.000 --> 01:29:03.000
Your son came home late. You call them orc. Make sure they weren't there.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:08.000
And they were regularly harassed by the police.

01:29:08.000 --> 01:29:09.000
What are they doing now?

01:29:09.000 --> 01:29:13.000
Well, one son actually is a lawyer.

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:19.000
He said unlike many other lawyers, he believes his clients.

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:24.000
When they say certain things happen, that's our youngest son.

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:33.000
And the other two are physicians, ones and nephrologists with a subspecialty and kidney transplant medication.

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:48.000
And the other has his MD, he's a hospitalist, but he also has a PhD in information, computers.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:58.000
And he's questioning the entire logic of mathematics.

01:29:58.000 --> 01:30:01.000
Your mother would be very proud of the question.

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:05.000
Right, somebody became professional, right?

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:13.000
Beginning in the 21st century and even before you were involved in a project as one of the instigators,

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:18.000
to gather the remembrances in the essays written by SNCC women,

01:30:18.000 --> 01:30:23.000
the result was a marvelous book published in 2020.

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:27.000
Going again with the introduction.

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:33.000
Well, you better give it just in case we didn't close the file properly.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:36.000
Okay, start where?

01:30:36.000 --> 01:30:38.000
You guys start with the introduction.

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:39.000
Okay, we'll go home.

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:42.000
All right.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:54.000
Early in the 21st century, you and a group of other women in SNCC began to compile a group of essays written by SNCC women talking about their experiences in the movement.

01:30:54.000 --> 01:30:59.000
The result was a wonderful collection called Hands on the Freedom Plow: Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC: Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC,

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:06.000
Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC, published in 2010 by the University of Illinois Press.

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:09.000
Show it to us and tell us something about it.

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:12.000
Hands on the Freedom Plow: Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC: Personal Accounts by Women in SNCC.

01:31:12.000 --> 01:31:19.000
And it's the stories of 52 women who are active in the civil rights movement in projects connected with SNCC.

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:26.000
It has the stories of most of the women were college students at the time,

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:35.000
but we also have included women who were middle-aged activists, white women, black women.

01:31:35.000 --> 01:31:38.000
There are two Hispanic women in the book.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:39.000
So.

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:44.000
And for those of you watching this now into the future, it is also available in paperback edition.

01:31:44.000 --> 01:31:45.000
Yes.

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:47.000
And we recommend it highly.

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:50.000
Martha, noona, thank you very much for being with us.

01:31:50.000 --> 01:31:52.000
This has been a real pleasure for us.

01:31:52.000 --> 01:31:54.000
Thank you.

01:31:54.000 --> 01:32:02.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

